election_record.label: Virginia 1808 Electoral College

overview.note: The Augusta Chronicle (Augusta, GA) lists the Madison ticket with 14665 votes, the Monroe ticket with 3408 votes and the Pinckney ticket with 760 votes, as does the The Virginia Argus (Richmond, VA) of November 25, 1808. However, it should be noted that while the Augusta Chronicle only lists totals, the The Virginia Argus (Richmond, VA) lists numbers by county as well, and several counties are not included on their list (Giles, Greensville, Henry, Mason, Monroe, Randolph and Shenandoah).
Peter Bailey replaced John Lucas on the Monroe ticket.
Richard Brent replaced Daniel Carrol Brent on the Monroe ticket.
Henry Saint George Tucker replaced Robert Mackie on the Monroe ticket.
The Pinckney ticket was adopted at Staunton on October 22, 1808 and appeared in the The Virginia Argus (Richmond, VA) on November 4, 1808.

"Baltimore, Jan 28. Extract of a letter from a member of the assembly of Virginia, to his friend in Washington, dated 22d January. 'Two caucuses were held here last night, on the subject of the Presidential election - one by the friends of Mr. Madison, and the other by the friends of Mr. Munroe. The results of which was that there were 134 members of the Legislature for Mr. Madison, and 57 for Mr. Munroe. The friends of Mr. Madison formed their Electoral ticket and Corresponding committees.'" Frederick-Town Herald (Fredericktown, MD). January 30, 1808. An almost identical item is published in The True American and Commercial Advertiser (Philadelphia, PA), February 2, 1808; Pittsfield Sun, February 13, 1808; and Crawford Weekly Messenger (Meadsville), February 18, 1808.

"The federal members, we understand, did not attend either meeting, but we believe they inclined to favour Mr. Monroe, and we are also of opinion, that the federalists through the state, if they MUST vote for Mr. Monroe or Mr. Madison, they will vote for the former." Norfolk Gazette and Publick Ledger (Norfolk, VA). January 28, 1808.

"At a meeting, agreeable to notice, of the Federal Republicans of the city of Richmond and town of Manchester, held at the Bell Tavern, in the city of Richmond, on Monday the 17th October 1808, to decide upon the candidate whom they will support at the ensuing election of the president of the United States. Doctor James McClury was unanimously chosen Chairman, and Doctor John Adams, Secretary to the meeting - After which, the following Resolutions were unanimously adopted. 1. Reduced by the tyranny of the General Ticket Law, to the necessity of abandoning our choice, and bestowing our suffrages on one of the Democratic candidates for the Presidency of the United States, and believing that of these the election of James Monroe would most essentially promote the welfare of the nation. Resolved, That this meeting will support the Ticket of the said James Monroe, at the ensuing election." Norfolk Gazette and Publick Ledger (Norfolk, VA), October 21, 1808; and The Freeman's Journal and Philadelphia Mercantile Advertiser (Philadelphia, PA), October 22, 1808.

sub_unit.name: Augusta
sub_unit.note: The Norfolk Gazette and Publick Ledger (Norfolk, VA) lists the Madison ticket with 336 votes, the Monroe ticket with 0 votes and the Pinckney ticket with 328 votes.
Die Virginische Volksberichter, und Neumarketer Wochenschrift (New Market, VA) lists the James Madison ticket with 344 votes and the Charles C. Pinckney ticket with 336.

sub_unit.name: Williamsburg
sub_unit.note: At the time, Williamsburg was split between James City County and York County and was not yet an independent city. The votes in Williamsburg appear to have been reported independently of either county.
